---
source: crates/jig-cli/src/context.rs
expression: render_client_list_human()
---
Client renderings — how each client reshapes the tool surface before the model
sees it. Every implemented variant is derived from a citable public source; a
client whose rendering no source establishes is listed as unknown and refused,
never guessed.

  ✓ api             verified      Raw provider API
      tool names, descriptions and schemas exactly as the server sent them
      source: jig's own request — the body `jig bench` sends, rendered by
              jig_core::bench::render_request_parts

  ~ claude-code     approximated  Claude Code
      prefixes each tool name with `mcp__<server>__`
      source: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/hooks — "MCP tools follow the naming pattern
              `mcp__<server>__<tool>`"
      not established: whether the description or input schema is rewritten, and what
                       system-prompt framing is added — Claude Code is closed-source, so
                       only the name format is citable

  ✓ vscode          verified      VS Code / GitHub Copilot
      prefixes names as `mcp_<server>_`, prefix capped at 18 chars and id at 64; description
      and schema pass through unmodified
      source: microsoft/vscode, src/vs/workbench/contrib/mcp/common/mcpTypes.ts
              (McpToolName.Prefix='mcp_', MaxPrefixLen=18, MaxLength=64) and
              mcpLanguageModelToolContribution.ts (modelDescription =
              definition.description, inputSchema = definition.inputSchema)
      not established: the final serialization into the provider HTTP payload happens in the
                       Copilot extension layer, which is not open-source — the name
                       transform and the description/schema pass-through are verified, the
                       last hop is not

  ✓ openai-agents   verified      OpenAI Agents SDK (Python)
      no transformation by default — identical to the raw API rendering
      source: openai/openai-agents-python, src/agents/mcp/util.py —
              `include_server_in_tool_names` defaults to False, so `tool_public_name` is the
              raw MCP tool name; description and schema are passed through
      not established: the opt-in `include_server_in_tool_names=True` path yields
                       `mcp_<server>__<tool>`; jig renders the documented default, not the
                       opt-in

  · claude-desktop  unknown       Claude Desktop
      not established — no renderer implemented
      source: checked https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/develop/connect-local-servers and
              Anthropic's Claude Desktop documentation: both cover configuration, server
              startup and the approval UI, and state nothing about tool naming or rendering.
              Closed-source.
      not established: the entire rendering

  · cursor          unknown       Cursor
      not established — no renderer implemented
      source: checked https://cursor.com/docs/context/mcp and
              https://cursor.com/docs/agent/tools: neither documents a name transformation
              nor a tool-definition limit. The widely-repeated "40 tool limit" appears only
              in community forum threads, which do not establish behaviour. Closed-source.
      not established: the entire rendering

`--client api` (the default) is the raw provider request `jig bench` sends.
For any other client the reported delta covers only the cited transformation, so it
is a lower bound on that client's true context cost.
